list-item.p:
Graph Construction Layer: The first layer depicts the core entities of insurance as nodes in the graph, which is constructed dynamically. To illustrate, nodes in the graph represent policyholders, insured items, third parties, brokers, and corporate ties. Two nodes are connected with an edge, which is defined by the various relations we have foundfamilial ties, same addresses, same vendors, supply-chain associations, or behavior, depending on telematics. Data streams (event logs, IoT telemetries, claims activity) are processed almost re. With the help of a distributed streaming platform like Apache Kafka, the model can now have a live graph with minimum latency. The dynamic closed relational networks depicted in the graph allow the model to be very sensitive to relationships and risk aggregations that are hidden when traditional tabular approaches are used,Graph message passing.
\begin{equation*}
\begin{gathered}
h_{\mathcal{V}}^{(0)}=W_{0} x_{\mathcal{V}}, \quad m_{\mathcal{V}}^{(k)}=\sum_{u \in \mathcal{N}(\mathcal{V})} \alpha_{u \mathcal{V}}^{(k)} W_{m}^{(k)} h_{\mathcal{u}}^{(k-1)}, \\
h_{\mathcal{V}}^{(k)}=\sigma\left(W_{h}^{(k)}\left[h_{\mathcal{V}}^{(k-1)} \vert m_{\mathcal{V}}^{(k)}\right]\right)
\end{gathered}
\end{equation*}
with attention weights $\alpha_{u v}^{(k)}=\operatorname{softmax}_{u}\left(a\left(h_{u}^{(k-1)}, h_{v}^{(k-1)}\right)\right)$

Causal Inference Module: In order to mitigate the adverse implications of spurious correlations and fairness concerns, our model utilizes a causal inference layer. This causal inference layer can use attachment approaches like Double Machine Learning (DML) to estimate causal effects or NOTEARS for structure learning directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) from observational data [14]. Specifically, it identifies causally-relevant features and pathways especially when node features can vary by things like protected or regulated variables (i.e. gender, geography). The advantage of this structure is that it improves the model's generalizability across demographic changes and regulatory constraints, and it mitigates the risk of overfitting to historically biased data. Causal signal and fairness regulization.
\begin{equation*}
\tilde{h}_{\mathcal{V}}^{(k)}=h_{\mathcal{V}}^{(k)}+R_{\text {causal }}(\mathcal{V}),
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{L}_{\text {causal }}=\sum_{j}\left(\widehat{\mathcal{T}}_{j}+\mathcal{T}_{j}^{*}\right)^{2}+\gamma \operatorname{Dep}(f(X), Z \text { protected })
\end{equation*}
Where $\quad \widehat{\mathcal{T}}_{j} \quad$ are treatment-effect estimates from DML/NOTEARS-derived structure, and Dep ($\cdot$) penalizes dependence on protected attributes or their proxies.

Graph-aware attention.
\begin{equation*}
\begin{array}{r}
\mathcal{Q}=X W_{Q}, K=X W_{K}, V=X W_{V}, Z=\operatorname{MHAttn}(Q, K, V) \\
=\text { Concat }_{h} \operatorname{softmax}\left(\frac{Q_{h} K_{h}}{\sqrt{d / H}}\right) V_{h}
\end{array}
\end{equation*}

We report Demographic Parity Gap (DPG):
\begin{equation*}
D P G=\vert\mathbb{E}[\hat{Y} \mid Z=1]-\mathbb{E}[\hat{Y} \mid Z=0]\vert
\end{equation*}
Where Z is a protected-group indicator and $\hat{Y}$ the predicted risk /decision score.
